segments.text: We publish booklets, and we give them information at closing, and we visit with all the landscape architects and architectural, I mean, landscape firms that operate in the woodlands to try to get them to think about this natural environment and saving trees.
So that's an ongoing process.
Yeah, every year we have something called Arbor Day, and we've given away, how many of them?
330 pounds.
seedlings and small trees, and people stand in line to get those trees, and they take them home, and they plant them in the yard.
They plant them.
And we did get to have the wildflower festival.
Wildflowers are deeply part of the image of the woodlands.
Lady Bird Johnson has been here for several seminars.
She's deeply involved in wildflowers.
Texas wildflowers are something we plant and cultivate every year and have a very well-defined program to propagate those.
At what point following 86 did you feel like you were rounding the hump, let's say, of the financial priority?
You may not have felt that way yet.
I guess we're still working on it.
Statistically, the third quarter of 1987 is when
The Houston economy started rebounding.
I think we gained 12,000 jobs in Houston in the third quarter of 1987 after having lost 200,000.
That was the first time you could see it coming back.
In 1988, I think we gained maybe 30,000 jobs at about that level, maybe 40,000 jobs in 1989.
Also, according to a study done by Barton Smith at the University of Houston, you probably know,
Houston is now about 60% energy-dependent, where it was 80% energy-dependent.
And the strengths are, you know, the port of Houston, it's number one in the nation in terms of export tonnage.
And most of that is not petroleum-related.
It's grain and foodstuffs and things like that.
The NASA Space Center, of course, has come back strongly during the downturn.
During that downturn, we were blessed, too, with the largest highway construction program ever undertaken in this region.
More than a billion dollars a year was spent on highway construction in the Houston region, which exceeded any other state in the nation except California for a five-year period of time.
And, of course, the tremendous growth and expansion of the Texas Medical Center, a $5 billion expansion program underway out there, and it's still ongoing.
really helped the Houston economy.
Compact Computer came into being and didn't exist in 1982.
And that's one of the major companies in this country.
And it's located 20 miles away.
The biotechnology industry and startup companies that have come out of that.
Dr. Dominic Lamb, you'll enjoy that interview.
He's a very interesting, intelligent, bright, energetic person.
You'll get a lot from Dr. Lamb.
There was another matter I was going to mention.
By 88, you can see things moving in the right direction.
89 was a good year.
This year, we'll have a record year in home sales.
So far, we've sold almost $120 billion worth of homes, $120 million worth of homes, $120 million worth of new homes this year.
Oh, no, the Barton Smith study.
We had him conduct a study to determine what is the impact of the Woodlands on the economy of Montgomery County.
In the early days, the Woodlands was not well accepted by Montgomery County.

great deal of suspicion doubt and uncertainty even hostility from the hostility and there is still some of that but it's it's beginning to wane and obviously it's not so bad but the interesting thing about that study is that now the woodlands constitutes 17 of the tax base in the county it is the biggest single taxpaying entity in the county today at one time the connor oil field

was the dominant economic generator for taxes in the county and now the woodlands exceeds and when i say the woodlands i mean all the homes collectively the woodland pays more taxes than the common law bill pays to support schools and the county government we also now constitute about 16 percent of the voting population in the county
The community is predominantly Republican, predominantly conservative, and it's changed the shape of politics within the county.
When I moved here 20-something years ago into Montgomery County, you could not find anyone who would profess to be a Republican, except Dr. Wally Wilkerson, who was part of the Republican Party.
Today, you can't find anybody who agrees that they're a Democrat.
Local office holders who originally were elected as Democrats have now changed to the Republican Party for fear of being defeated.
The Woodlands has done, I think, a number of positive things for the county.
It's helped create economic growth.
It's helped create jobs.
It's provided, I think, the numbers, 25% of the retail sales are generated by people who live in the Woodlands.
That's not 25% retail sales occurring in the Woodlands.
But the population of the women's generates 25% of the retail sales.
Has this study been published?
I'll give you a copy of it.
I think we'd like that.
Jack, could you see it?
It's interesting reading.
And I got Dr. Smith to do it, so it would be objective.
We could do it, but that would not be held to be fairly objective.
Credibility would be questioned, but...
This will give you some good background information from a third-party source.
It's got a good executive summary, and then he kind of gets involved in the science of evaluating demographics and economic evaluation.
The executive summary makes more exciting reading than the methodology.
Well, you know, we've got the same over in the Gulf, and we've got oil prices that went down $5 a barrel yesterday, and I don't know what they've done today, and there is a devastating
financial conditions for financing real estate nationally.
And while the market is good in the Houston region, financial institutions don't look favorably upon real estate financing.
So I think it's going to have some detrimental effect on Houston, even though we're doing much better than the nation as a whole.
We still look to the money-centered banks for a lot of financing.
And I don't think that it's going to be as generous as we would like for it to be.
But so far we've spent $2 billion in the river, total.
$2 billion has been invested by all parties in the river.
A billion dollars of that is in residential homes owned by third parties.
The rest of it's in schools and churches and office buildings and research facilities and land development and those kinds of things.
The total investment in the woodlands will be about $12 billion by all parties.
And the population will be somewhere around 150,000 people.
And we anticipate having about 80,000 permanent jobs.
Someone asked, when are you going to finish developing the woodlands?
And the very clear answer is that we never will, because no city is ever complete.
I don't think you've ever driven through any city in this country where you could
they have finished.
I mean, there will always be redevelopment, reconstruction of buildings, replacement of housing.
But essentially, most of the development will have occurred by the year 2027, 2020, 2030.
Somewhere in that range.
We have a very definite plan year by year, unit by unit.
You asked about the

the strategy for developing it that we have a an economic model that we update annually that looks forward and takes into account changes since we last did it is that in-house is that done in there we do it with some outside consulting help but it's a it's an in-house document that we could use for our own planning purposes and we don't publish that well do you see that this kind of expansion population growth as being a threat or a great difficulty in uh
continuing to manage the environment and the quality of life type situation, or do you feel quite comfortable that can be accommodated?
I think it can be accomplished, but it's becoming more complicated.
I think the 1990s is going to be the decade of the environment.
We see things like concern about hazardous waste, endangered species, the wetlands, the Clean Air Act.
All of those things are going to come to bear.
Frankly, I don't think in the future you're going to see very many large-scale communities like the woodlands undertaken in the future for those very reasons.
There's so much uncertainty over the life span of developing a community like this that you deal with a lot of uncertainties, a lot of risk involved.
You have so much front-end investment that you have to recoup out of

out of the assumption of later development no i don't i don't think you probably will i think the government involvement should be one of providing incentives and not providing roadblocks actually you know some people look at the woodlands as a government-sponsored community
We borrowed $50 million to start the development of the Woodlands, but we're paying that back.
That was a loan.
That was not a gift from heaven.

It was a little lower interest rate, but when you add to it all the administrative cost of monitoring that for the government and reporting and the hassle you go through, I'm not sure it was a good bargain.
George Mitchell will tell you it was a tremendous bargain, but I lived over here working on those reports that had to go in, and I was
There was a cost attached to that.
But I think the environment is going to be a great challenge in the future.
We, I think, tried to address it very well.
And I think we've done a pretty good job of it.
But I think there are going to be more and more rules and regulations promulgated without a clear understanding of the impact.
It's going to cause uncertainty and delays.
And the delays is money.
When you get one of these started, you really need to move along with it.
You can't have periods of time when you do nothing.
What projects are you really devoting most of your time to right now?
Or is there any kind of affinity like that?
Well, I'm pretty well involved in all the projects that are going on.
It's hard in a community like this to separate it into a series of projects.
They're all interrelated.
Right now, this week, we have the formal opening of the new 18-hole golf course designed by Arnold Palmer.
And we are expanding the country club and the large... What is that opening?
It's on the 30th.
You're invited.
Thank you, sir.
It's coming at 11 o'clock.
But we're...

Right now, after being here 15 years, a number of our facilities are 15 years old, and we have had an ongoing refurbishing program, but right now it's a little more intensive than it has been in the past.
We've renovated the conference center, updated the guest rooms, enlarging the country club, separating the conference center from the country club for their two separate entities over there.
We're enlarging the golf facilities because the
The membership has grown tremendously.
We're engaged in, continually engaged in this economic development program and encouraging businesses to locate here.
And the main thrust in that, again, would be right now is in the medical area, in the, say, in the umbrella of the advanced research area.
And also well-established companies looking for a home.
For example, we have the products testing laboratory for Penzol here, a well-established company.
Betts Process Chemical has a major operation here.
Up in the Trade Center, you may or may not have seen it, it's a rail to serve Trade Center and major distribution centers there owned by Michelin Tire, Kraft Food, Eckerd Drug,
The distribution outlet for McDonald's, as well as Burger King are there.
Are you continuing that expansion?
Yeah.
As a matter of fact, most of our buildings are completely full there.
We have an ongoing program to enhance and improve the mobility of the region through the encouragement of improving highways.
We've created here in the Woodlands, and I think this is kind of unique, we've created a commuter van system.
and also commuter bus parking ride system.
We're outside the service area of the Houston Metro, so they could not bring buses into the woodlands.
So we worked through the county and got a federal grant and we built a parking ride lot and we financed the buses.

it's now being operated by brazos transit authority which is located in brian right they do a good job yeah they do a good job here too so we've been able to take uh you know four or five six hundred cars off the highway by creating uh alternative systems for transportation is there no internal transportation yeah would you anticipate ever having to do something like that well we're setting aside rights aways and the provision for that to occur
There's no defined plan to make it happen currently.
Most of those that have been attempted have failed.
Without some heavy subsidy, it's hard to, even up to Brian, I don't know.
What about rail service?
Do you need to teach them anything in monorail or anything like that in the Houston-Dallas connection?
Well, that's always a possibility, and part of the
There's a plan for this high-speed rail from Dallas to Houston and to San Antonio, and there are a couple of alternate routes for that, both to the west of the Woodlands.
They would not come through the Woodlands, so I don't think we'd be exposed to that opportunity, but we do have a rail system here in Front Door.
There's great debate in the city of Houston, as you know right now, about heavy rail, whether or not to have it, and if so, where, and who pays for it.
If, as you commented, the 90s become the decade of the environment, highway building, if it's pursued logically, would diminish, I would think.
Alternative, as you suggested, alternative modes would have to then increase.
Yeah, I think you're going to see those pressures.
I think you're exactly right.
With respect to the specific question about rail, I don't think that's in the immediate 10-year horizon just because of cost, time to build it, who owns it and how it operates.
There are a lot of questions that need to be answered about rail before it's implemented anywhere in the Houston region, I think.
Great debate about that.
What about recreation as an economic investment?
That's a good question.
Back when I got started in the real estate development business, developers typically built golf courses to help sell land and then hope they didn't lose too much money and usually gave it away to

The members, if they would take it or sell it to someone for a small number of dollars, Club Corporation of America became wealthy by taking over clubs that developers didn't know how to run or that members couldn't operate.
Today, that's changed.
Golf is a business, and it's a profitable business.
We just finished a study looking at golf meets in the woodlands.
Right now, we have four 18-hole golf courses.
One of them is a tournament players course, which is in fact a day-to-day course.
You don't have to be a member to play.
We have one course for the conferees who visit the conference center for recreational purposes.
And we have two 18-hole courses set aside for country club membership.
And we had the firm by the name of Real Estate Research Associates of California do a comprehensive study course looking at the total golf needs
in demand throughout the life of the Woodlands.
And in total, we need 10 golf courses in the Woodlands, 10 18-hole golf courses.
So we need six more than we have today.

And that would be a combination of the second tournament players course, which we have the right to build, a 36-hole daily fee course, a public course, for those who cannot afford or choose not to belong to a country club,
And then a more exclusive country club than the one we have today, a higher end club, maybe an equity club where the members would own that.
We're combining that now with our land planning for the remaining portions of the woodlands to make sure we set aside enough land in the right place to accommodate those golfing needs.
Yeah.
We've got all the real estate falls under... We've got two parcels of land in Colorado, one between Aspen and Snowmass and one at Steamboat Springs.
And the regulatory environment up there is a morass.
Yeah, dealing with everybody.
Forest Service is the one who grants permits, but you deal with everyone who chooses to deal with you.
But in the area between Aspen and Snowmass, we have developed about 800 acres of land.
And have sold lots to individuals who have built homes.
And that's in the very beautiful Owl Creek Valley that extends the entire distance from the town of Aspen to the town of Snowmass.
And in Steamboat Springs, we have 3,000 acres of land that we own jointly with a third party.
And there, we're actively trying to get a permit to build a ski mountain.
And that one will take on a different character from what we have in Aspen.
has been very low density.
The only thing that, you know, recreation ties nicely with your quality of life and with the types of your medical care, atmosphere, and all of that.
Even with the environmental.
The jogging path.
Yeah.
You asked about other recreational things here in the Woodlands, and you mentioned jogging path.
That's probably the single most popular recreational amenity we have.
We have 53 miles of pathway.
And it costs...
$20 a foot to build that.
Is that your cost?
$10,000 a month.
$5 to $10 million invested in this pathway.
I mean, that's a tremendous investment in a recreational facility.
But it's used by everybody.
Kids on bicycles, people out for exercise, people both jogging and riding bicycles and
actually commuting in some cases from home to school and from home to shopping.
We've got some of the retirement communities located close to the shopping center, and you see people in wheelchairs walking down and moving down a pathway to go to the grocery store.
So it's kind of a nice feel to it.
We have a swimming athletic center, which is
Olympic quality in terms of its facilities.
As a matter of fact, Olympic tryouts are held there, and we're in the process of enlarging and upgrading that currently.
I think in summary, I really don't know how much time you wanted to give us, but...
I've still got a couple of questions.
Okay, you go ahead.
Well, one of the things which you started, and then we got distracted away from it.
You mentioned some of the things that in the future...
not that they're worried, but the things you're planning to do.
The other side of that coin is, what are the future incentives or the initiatives that you perceive?
Are there future initiatives?
Is it going to be business as usual, or are there other initiatives that the Woodlands is going to develop in the next two to three decades?
Well, yeah, there are very specific things that we need to develop in the next several decades.
One is town center.
Town center is
well-defined on paper, still defined if you try to find it.
But it will include about 17 million square feet of office space, which is equivalent to the downtown of probably Cincinnati, if you measure in square footage.
But it will include a regional shopping mall, and it will be the urbanized center for Northeastern.
Not only the urbanized center for Woodlands, but we look at that as a focal point for business in Northeastern.
It's a
Termination of the Hardy Toll Road is on I-45.
It's the intersection of some major east-west roadways under design and partially under construction.
And it will be the center of population for more than a million people.
So we look at that as a big item on our agenda for the next 10 to 15 years.
We look at the research forest only at beginning stages right now.
And we would hope that
we would have 15,000, 20,000 jobs in the research forest over the next 20 years.
And in fact, do things like have been done in the research triangle of North Carolina, or around the Stanford and the Silicon Valley, or Route 128 in Boston.
So that's a long-term goal and objective.
We work on it every day.
And we try not to lose sense of direction of where we're trying to get to and be discouraged if we haven't gotten there as quickly as we'd like.
Those are two very big elements.

uh beyond that the the continuation of a quality residential program on the remaining lands in the woodlands that continues to provide housing opportunities for the secretary and the clerk in the grocery store as well as the chairman of the board all done in a tasteful way neighborhoods that are close together so you get the social intermixing of

school level anyway public schools where you don't have an elitist side of town and a poor side of town so that's an objective we had from the beginning and we still pursue we have a couple of major lakes we'd like to build in the woods for recreational purposes and that's going to take some regulatory approvals governmental health and things like that but that's part of the mission that we
look at as being important to us.
Let me ask you a couple of specific questions.
My brother's a city manager in Las Vegas.
We've been doing that for more than a dozen years.
I called him several months ago, or actually a better part of a year ago, when we first started kicking around.
Well, over the years I've talked to them, I'm completely at sea when it comes to the niceties or the crudities, however you want to look at it.
I've run in a community.
Both definitions are right.
You mentioned that the Woodlands is non-incorporated.
That's right.
Will it be?
Well, let me give you the legal side and then maybe the practical side, a little background.
Right now we have a community association.
It was formed when the Woodlands was created.
and is supported financially by assessments applied against all properties that have been developed in the river.
And it has about a $6 million budget now.

And it provides all the municipal services that the city would provide, including the fire department, the collection of garbage, the street escape maintenance, neighborhood watch programs, emergency medical services, street lights, mowing grass, maintaining the parks and pathways.
It does everything the city would do.
And the outlook is for that mechanism to continue until one of two things happens.
The woodlands become separately incorporated in the city, or it's incorporated into the corporate boundaries of the city of Houston.
And under current state law, the woodlands is in the extracurricular jurisdiction of the city of Houston.
And the city of Houston has the right and authority to annex the woodlands any time it would like to do that.
As a practical matter, I don't think they will for another year for a couple reasons.
One, we're not contiguous to the existing boundaries of the city of Houston, and they would have to step over a lot of the land that would not be in their corporate boundaries.
And two, they're not going to annex the woodlands as long as there is a
significant debt existing in the municipal utility districts that have been created to provide utilities until that debt is paid down.
I would think that over the next 20 years, unless state law changes, that Woodlands will become part of the City of Houston.
Is that an assumption built into your strategic plans?
Yes.
I'll go on to say, too, that if you took a vote in the Woodlands today, there'd probably be 90% of the people who would choose not to be in the city of Houston and maybe 10% who would.
So it's not necessarily a popular decision.
But when you think about it on a regional basis and step aside from the selfish, what's best for me question,

Cities up in the northeastern part of the country and other parts of the country have been choked, small incorporated cities surrounding them, productive people moving out of the inner city, living and paying taxes in these small incorporated areas.
And the central city has no tax base or declining tax base to provide essential services, the airport, the library, the museum, the streets that lead to the jobs where people work.

and philosophically george mitchell felt that the city of houston needed to have the ability to continue to annex land and grow as it could provide services for those areas so by contract the woodlands is included in etj it was not it was not geographically situated to be included in etj but by contract it is now included in etj isn't that
I mean, a lot of what you said, you know, were you to go, well, one, does the community in fact know that?
Yes.
They do know that?
Isn't that then a potential source of some grievous conflict in the future?
Yes.
Which means, I mean, what's going to happen?
Well, right now the approach, and I think the realistic response is that nothing is going to happen for a period of time.

city of houston is not going to annex it with them for a period of time you know likelihood yeah it's a sleeping dog that's going to wake up well it slept in a place called clear lake city until the residents there challenged the system and under state law an area can if it wants to separately incorporate it first has to ask the city in whose

etj it resides to annex them and if the city refuses to do that then they can incorporate the clear lake city asked the question and they were annexed into the city of houston and that was not a pleasant set of circumstances existed for a number of years as you look around houston every major large-scale community is in etj in the city of houston it's not unique to the woodland no i know so wherever you uh
around the city of Houston, you're faced with the same issue.
So it's not a unique Woodlands question.
It's a regional issue.
But the distinction is, I mean, forgive me, but the distinction is those communities, this is a corporation running a community.
That isn't happening.
Kingwood is, too.
Oh, is it?
Fair Lake City is, too.
Because what I would...

you know, at least there'd be a nagging headache in the back of my skull that at some point, instead of animosity being turned toward the city of Houston or some other place, that I'm going to catch it in my lap, you know.

Well, under the community association that we have here, it's a representative form of government that residents elect representatives to serve on their behalf on the board of directors that addresses all the municipal services and charges for those services that

the scope of delivering those services and in fact in 1992 the residents will control that wca board the community association board and the developer will no longer control that one so it's not that the corporation controls the community uh the residents will control the community you're in the middle of that transfer right now yeah right that was my second question we're in the transition that takes place in 1992 and
We're trying to go through the discussion of trying to prepare the community for that happening.
And right now, frankly, there is some confusion.
It's a complicated issue.
Most people don't think about it day to day.
It's not something they deal with.
And then when confronted with the notion that something's going to happen, the natural reaction is, if it's changing, I need to be concerned about it.
And then they try to learn quickly what they need to be concerned about.
And we're going through a very lengthy educational process now to make sure they don't misunderstand that we're the bad guys.
Sure.
That was my other question.
As the privatization of city management or government proceeds, what's your role?
How will you continue to influence or affect the quality of life issues, the infrastructure, the
that you've worked so hard to establish.
Well, we hope we put in place a framework with respect to those areas already developed that will last long after the development is gone.
That was the, I don't like the word scheme, that was the concept.
To put in place a form of quasi-government.
Residents would run, control, operate, and take care of their own needs.
Our intent is not to be here forever.
probably seems that we will be.
We'll be here for a long time.
But in 1992, when this first community association control transfers to the residents, a second community association will be formed to carry out the development mission on lands not yet developed.
So we will, in essence, control.
We'll have the capacity to control the undeveloped lands.
with respect to lands already developed, the residents will control that.
So there's a transfer of control with respect to what's already been done.
In terms of residential development, you're about halfway where you anticipate being?
No.
No, we've got 30,000 people live here, 150,000.
150,000, you're assuming.
No, whatever percent that is.
You've got a lot to do.
20% somewhere.
But it's an accelerating pace.
And if we don't have eight years of economic hardship, maybe we'll move along faster.
We're 16 years old, and we've been in the doldrums eight of those 16 years.
So I think our progress has been, I think, surprisingly good, considering what's happening.
Well, I think you're right.
I think you're right.
You know, the rest of the country has been in college stations.
You've still been pretty active.
Let me ask one last question, and then I'll shut up.
And you may find this impertinent.
But it's something that I wondered about as I talked with Mr. Richmond, Mr. Brown, and now you.
What would happen to the Woodlands if George Mitchell died tomorrow?
Well, the Woodlands Corporation is a wholly owned subsidiary of a public corporation.
George, in fact, owns 62% of the stock of that corporation, but it is publicly held.
and will have an ongoing life should something unfortunate happen to Mr. Mitchell.
I'm not privy to how his estate would be managed.
I would expect that a great portion of it probably would go into a foundation.
And I would not expect any great changes over the short term.
Over a longer period of time, I don't guess I would be capable of addressing that.
But there's enough framework in the Woodlands, just talking about the Woodlands itself and the community of the Woodlands.

There's enough framework here already in place and enough initiatives in place, and it's a market that vitality has been established to the point where I think it could have an ongoing life beyond this commission.
You feel that the strategic plans you've developed and the machinery of those are going to continue on regardless?
Yeah.
There may be some modification to it, but I come back to the earlier statements.
What we try to do is build fabric in the community that gives the community ongoing life and set into place some institutions that have a life of its own.
And it will be a viable community.
You know, a town of 30,000 people is not a small town.
And it's got a lot of elements in it that are necessary to make it function, even if it's leading up others.
By 1992, basically, the Woodlands Corporation would be another business located in the Woodlands City, I'd say, in the transfer authority.
Except that they'll still be developing.
They'll still be developing.
We're going to continue to develop.
In 1992, you won't be able to tell any difference visually if you drive in here.
And if you live here, you probably won't notice any difference either.
Legally, there will be some changes that take place.
But I think with respect to the development concept, the quality of what we're doing, the pace at which we're doing it, the way it's financed, there'll be little or no change to that.
Well, good.
We probably shouldn't have put it on the board.
Well, we haven't written that position.
I like to talk about the Woodlands.
Well, it's exciting.
Yeah, it's a unique opportunity, a unique place.
It's nice to have a sense of pride in what you're doing.
I guess the most satisfying things I can do is not sit here in the office, but occasionally on the weekend drive around and see what's happening.
I mean, it's kind of impressive when you get out and look at all the things that have happened.
And we got caught up in the fires like anyone else.
There's a crisis today or a crisis tomorrow.
We addressed that, and we'd like to think we always have a long-range vision, but in truth and in fact, you have daily things that you need to do.
It's nice to back away occasionally and reflect on what has happened and what can't happen.
And we've got a staff of people who have been here a long time.
That was my next question.
How do you work?
Do you have staff meetings regularly?
Yeah, we have staff meetings and planning meetings and meetings on special issues.
But most of our employees have been with us 10, 15 years and been working together as a team for that period of time.
We don't have a lot of turnover.
And you don't have to have quite as many meetings when people have been around that long.
Everyone knows what they need to do and what's expected of them.

But in managing this process, we have a staff meeting once a week where our key managers get together and talk about the issues and try to stay away from numbers and details, but look at the big picture.
Then we have specific planning meetings in the residential communities and also in the commercial and retail areas.
We have staff groups.
Jack provides advertising and VR services to the operating units.
Each operating unit doesn't have an advertising and VR person.
We have centralized
engineering and construction group.
We have a centralized land planning group.
We have a centralized legal, accounting, financial services.
And then we have essentially three operating groups.
We have a residential group, a commercial industrial group, and we have a hospitality group.
Those are the three components of the Woodlands community.
And then we have
Another group that we call Mitchell Southwest that takes care of all the properties not in the woods, in Galveston Island.
We own 40,000 acres of timberland between here and College Station.
We have resort properties on Galveston, on Lake Travis, Lake Livingston.
And that's taken care of by a separate group.
That's a good summary.
The stuff that Mr. Mitchell does,
The restoration stuff, I'm guessing.
No, we provide the technical services.
That's all his money, all his initiative.
We have a couple architects that work in our planning group that help him select architects, especially trained in renovation work.
We oversee some of the construction for him, and we are reimbursed on a time basis for the work we provide for him.
That's basically like a contractual contract.
Yeah, right.
